The Readonly Modifier

The `readonly` modifier makes a property immutable after initialization.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
class Config {
  readonly apiKey: string;
  readonly endpoint: string;

  constructor(apiKey: string, endpoint: string) {
    this.apiKey = apiKey;
    this.endpoint = endpoint;
  }
}

const config = new Config("abc", "https://api.example.com");
// config.apiKey = "new"; // Error: Cannot assign to readonly
```

### readonly with Constructor Parameters

```typescript
class Point {
  constructor(
    public readonly x: number,
    public readonly y: number
  ) {}
}

const p = new Point(3, 4);
console.log(p.x, p.y); // 3, 4
// p.x = 5; // Error: readonly
```

### readonly vs const

| Feature | readonly | const |
|---------|----------|-------|
| Scope | Class/interface properties | Variables |
| Assignment | Only in declaration or constructor | Only in declaration |
| Objects | Reference immutable, contents mutable | Reference immutable |

### Readonly Arrays

```typescript
class DataStore {
  readonly items: readonly number[] = [1, 2, 3];

  getItems(): readonly number[] {
    return this.items;
  }
}

const store = new DataStore();
// store.items.push(4); // Error: push does not exist on readonly
```

### Readonly in Interfaces

```typescript
interface User {
  readonly id: number;
  readonly createdAt: Date;
  name: string;
}

const user: User = {
  id: 1,
  createdAt: new Date(),
  name: "Alice"
};

// user.id = 2; // Error: readonly
user.name = "Bob"; // OK
```

> **Key Point:** Use `readonly` for properties that should not change after construction.

codeExample:
class ImmutablePerson {
  constructor(
    public readonly firstName: string,
    public readonly lastName: string,
    public readonly birthYear: number
  ) {}

  getAge(currentYear: number): number {
    return currentYear - this.birthYear;
  }
}

const person = new ImmutablePerson("Alice", "Smith", 1995);
console.log(person.firstName); // Alice

// Readonly array property
class TodoList {
  readonly items: readonly string[] = [];

  constructor(...items: string[]) {
    this.items = items; // Can assign in constructor
  }
}
